comment:
Im not necessarily mad about the mr/mrs potato head thing but as a kid who played with it, and now as a mom who has a child who would also be able to play with them.. it just feels unnecessary. Like really, there are people who identify as men/mr and people who identify as women/mrs - and then there are people who are inbetween. I feel like the mr and mrs potato head at its *xore* was already gender fluid in the sense that the "girl parts" and "guy parts" were interchangeable. So really.. they had a better "gender demographic" as the original if they really wanted to spin this into "look at us so progressive!" Why cant mr potato head like the girly lips? Why cant mr potato head still identify as a man despite having "girly lips". 

And of course this arguement is using their logic that a *potato* has to be gender neutral for the kids as though yhe plastic potato itself is any different between the mr and mrs. Really if I wanted to teach a lesson about identity and how nothing is strictly manly or girly mr and mrs potato head wouldve been a great example. Mr potato head can wear all the "girly" things and still be whatever "he, she or they" want to be be that mr, mrs, or undefined. Vice versa for mrs potato head.

But lets be clear - this isnt really gender neutrality. This isnt like they were expressly made for boys to like and expressly made for girls to like. This isnt changing blue or pink to yellow. This is just for media attention in my opinion as taking away mr and mrs is more or less a paper change. By their own logic mr and mrs potato head were already gender fluid so if any kid reallllly put stock into the idea of their identities being "mr" or "mrs" is perfectly fine. Just like I clearly identify with mrs but can sometimes where "boy shirts". The only thing that identifies my gender is me, not what I wear, not what I do. Mr potato head can still be mr potato head and be considered "gender neutral" as long as we teach kids that "mr" s dont have to wear ONLY "boy things".
